  "prompt": "What is human right?",
  "response": "Human rights are fundamental rights and freedoms that every individual is entitled to, regardless of their nationality, sex, ethnicity, religion, language, or any other status. These rights are inherent to all human beings, and they are based on the principles of dignity, equality, and respect.\n\nThe Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR), adopted by the United Nations General Assembly in 1948, is a foundational document that outlines these rights. Some of the key human rights include:\n\n1. **Right to Life, Liberty, and Personal Security**: Everyone has the right to live, to be free, and to feel safe.\n2. **Freedom from Discrimination**: All individuals are entitled to equal protection under the law, without discrimination.\n3. **Freedom of Expression**: Everyone has the right to express their opinions and ideas freely.\n4. **Right to Privacy, Family, Home, and Correspondence**: People have the right to privacy and to maintain relationships with their family.\n5. **Right to Education, Work, and Social Security**: Everyone should have access to education, the opportunity to work, and social security to ensure a basic standard of living.\n6. **Freedom of Thought, Conscience, and Religion**: Individuals have the right to think freely and to practice their religion or belief.\n7. **Right to Participate in Government**: People have the right to take part in their country's political processes, either directly or through freely chosen representatives.\n\nHuman rights are protected and promoted by various international treaties, national laws, and advocacy efforts by organizations such as Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch. Despite these efforts, violations of human rights still occur worldwide, making ongoing vigilance and action essential to upholding these fundamental principles.",
